  "text": "and with E nκmκ being the energy eigenvalue. We label the eigensolutions with three quantum numbers n, κ, m κ . The latter two have been defined in Eq. (2.8) (cf. also Appendix A; the reader should observe that, in contrast to the counterpart three-dimensional problem, in the present case the quantum number κ is a half-integer), while the first one -the principal quantum number n, is defined to be n = n r + |κ| + The radial quantum number n r appearing in Eq. (2.12) is defined so that the number of nodes of P nκmκ (r) in the open interval (0, ∞) is n r for κ − 1 2 (in that case n r ∈ N 0 ) and n r − 1 for κ 1 2 (in that case n r ∈ N + ). For Z = 0 and B = 0, no general method of obtaining analytical solutions to the system (2.10) is known, and consequently one is relied on the use of approximations. If the external magnetic field is weak, as it will be assumed from now on, one may exploit the Rayleigh-Schrödinger perturbation theory. To this end, we split the radial Hamiltonian (2.11) in the following manner: [CITATION_1] with the zeroth-order operator being the radial Dirac-Coulomb Hamiltonian",
